**Fruit of the Loom** is an [American](/wiki/United_States "United States")
company that manufactures [clothing](/wiki/Clothing "Clothing"), particularly
[underwear](/wiki/Undergarment "Undergarment"). The company's world
headquarters is in [Bowling Green, Kentucky](/wiki/Bowling_Green,_Kentucky
"Bowling Green, Kentucky"). Since 2002 it has been a subsidiary of [Berkshire
Hathaway](/wiki/Berkshire_Hathaway "Berkshire Hathaway").

## Company
profile[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Fruit_of_the_Loom&action=edit&section=1
"Edit section: Company profile")]

[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d3/FruitoftheLoomHQ.jpg/250px-
FruitoftheLoomHQ.jpg)](/wiki/File:FruitoftheLoomHQ.jpg)

[](/wiki/File:FruitoftheLoomHQ.jpg "Enlarge")

Fruit of the Loom headquarters building in [Bowling Green,
Kentucky](/wiki/Bowling_Green,_Kentucky "Bowling Green, Kentucky")

Fruit of the Loom is one of the largest manufacturers and marketers of men's
and boys' underwear, women's and girls' underwear, printable T-shirts and
fleece for the activewear industry, casualwear, women's jeanswear and
childrenswear. The company employs more than 32,400 people worldwide.

Fruit of the Loom also controls another long-known underwear brand,
[B.V.D.](/wiki/B.V.D. "B.V.D.") (Bradley, Voorhees, and Day). Other brands
also manufactured and sold by the company are [Funpals](/wiki/Funpals
"Funpals")/[FunGals](/wiki/FunGals "FunGals"), Screen Stars and
[Underoos](/wiki/Underoos "Underoos"). Brands once owned or marketed by Fruit
of the Loom include Gitano, Munsingwear, Salem Sportswear, and Pro Player,
which once had the [naming rights](/wiki/Naming_rights "Naming rights") to
what is now [Hard Rock Stadium](/wiki/Hard_Rock_Stadium "Hard Rock Stadium")
(originally [Joe Robbie](/wiki/Joe_Robbie "Joe Robbie") Stadium) in [Miami
Gardens, Florida](/wiki/Miami_Gardens,_Florida "Miami Gardens, Florida") from
1996 to 2005, despite bankruptcy by the parent company in 1999.[_[citation
needed](/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed "Wikipedia:Citation needed")_]

[Hanes](/wiki/Hanes "Hanes") and [Jockey](/wiki/Jockey_International "Jockey
International") are the main competitors of Fruit of the Loom.

The company's familiar logo comprising a red apple, leaves, green grapes,
currants, and purple grapes forms a widely recognizable trademark. The company
is a [vertically integrated](/wiki/Vertical_integration "Vertical
integration") manufacturer. In TV commercials for the brand, actors play the
roles of only four of the logo's parts: the apple, green grapes, purple
grapes, and leaves. The role of "Apple" is played by [Rad
Daly](/w/index.php?title=Rad_Daly&action=edit&redlink=1 "Rad Daly \(page does
not exist\)"), and the "Leaf" was at one time played by [Academy
Award](/wiki/Academy_Award "Academy Award")-winning actor [F. Murray
Abraham](/wiki/F._Murray_Abraham "F. Murray Abraham"), and has been played by
Gene Steichen since the Fruit Guys were re-introduced to the public in 2001.
"Green Grapes" is played by [Richard Steven
Horvitz](/wiki/Richard_Steven_Horvitz "Richard Steven Horvitz"). "Purple
Grapes" is played by Wayne Wilderson.

## History[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Fruit_of_the_Loom&action=edit&section=2
"Edit section: History")]

[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f4/Fruit_of_the_Loom_Muslin_newspaper_ad.png/220px-
Fruit_of_the_Loom_Muslin_newspaper_ad.png)](/wiki/File:Fruit_of_the_Loom_Muslin_newspaper_ad.png)

[](/wiki/File:Fruit_of_the_Loom_Muslin_newspaper_ad.png "Enlarge")

1921 newspaper ad for Fruit of the Loom [muslin](/wiki/Muslin "Muslin") fabric

The Fruit of the Loom brand dates back to 1851 in [Rhode
Island](/wiki/Rhode_Island "Rhode Island")[1][2] when [Robert
Knight](/wiki/Robert_Knight_\(industrialist\) "Robert Knight
\(industrialist\)"), a textile mill owner, visited his friend, Rufus Skeel.
Skeel owned a small shop in [Providence](/wiki/Providence,_Rhode_Island
"Providence, Rhode Island") that sold cloth from Knight's mill. Skeel's
daughter painted images of apples and applied them to the bolts of cloth. The
ones with the apple emblems proved most popular. Mr. Knight thought the labels
would be the perfect symbol for his trade name, Fruit of the [Loom](/wiki/Loom
"Loom") – an expression referring to clothes, paralleling the phrase "[fruit
of the womb](/w/index.php?title=Fruit_of_the_womb&action=edit&redlink=1 "Fruit
of the womb \(page does not exist\)")" meaning "children", which can be traced
back to use in the [Bible](/wiki/Bible "Bible") (Psalm 127:3).

In 1871, just one year after the first trademark laws were passed by Congress,
Knight received trademark number 418 for the brand "Fruit of the Loom".

Much of its athletic outerwear was sold under the "Pro Player" label, a now
defunct division.

The company was part of [Northwest Industries](/wiki/Northwest_Industries
"Northwest Industries"), Inc., until NWI was purchased by [William F.
Farley](/wiki/William_F._Farley "William F. Farley") in 1985 and renamed
Farley Industries, Inc.[3] Farley served as president, [chief executive
officer](/wiki/Chief_executive_officer "Chief executive officer") (CEO), and
majority shareholder for 15 years. Fruit of the Loom's sales revenue rose from
approximately $500 million at the time of NWI's purchase to roughly $2.5
billion nearly 15 years later. Debt financing, once seen as brilliant, proved
difficult to manage even as sales revenue quintupled.[_[citation
needed](/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed "Wikipedia:Citation needed")_]

On March 23, 1987, it sold its subsidiary [General
Battery](/w/index.php?title=General_Battery&action=edit&redlink=1 "General
Battery \(page does not exist\)") to [Exide Corporation](/wiki/Exide
"Exide").[4]

Fruit of the Loom filed for Chapter 11 [bankruptcy](/wiki/Bankruptcy
"Bankruptcy") protection in 1999 shortly after posting a net loss of $576.2
million.[5] Its 66 million shares of outstanding common stock dropped in value
from about $44 per share in early 1997 to just more than $1 by spring 2000.
Reasons for the bankruptcy are varied. A large debt load which was assumed in
the 1980s, a common practice at the time, did not help. William F. Farley, the
company's former [chairman](/wiki/Chairman "Chairman"), CEO, and [chief
operating officer](/wiki/Chief_operating_officer "Chief operating officer")
(COO), was forced out prior to bankruptcy in late 1999, after having piloted
the company into massive debt and unproductive business ventures, including
structuring the company into an off-shore entity in the Cayman Islands to
avoid taxes.[_[citation needed](/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed
"Wikipedia:Citation needed")_]

The company was bought from bankruptcy by [Berkshire
Hathaway](/wiki/Berkshire_Hathaway "Berkshire Hathaway") Corporation,
controlled by investor [Warren Buffett](/wiki/Warren_Buffett "Warren
Buffett"), who wanted the valuable brand. He agreed in January 2002 to
purchase the company for approximately $835 million in cash. The deal was
concluded on April 29, 2002. A condition of the purchase required that former
COO and then interim CEO John Holland remain available to be the CEO for the
company.[6]

The company purchased [Russell Corporation](/wiki/Russell_Corporation "Russell
Corporation"), effectively taking the former competitor private, in a deal
valued at $598.3 million that was completed August 1, 2006.[7]

The company announced the purchase of [VF Corporation](/wiki/VF_Corporation
"VF Corporation")'s intimate apparel company named Vanity Fair Intimates for
$350 million in cash on January 23, 2007.[8]

In 2010, Rick Medlin was named president and CEO of Fruit of the Loom.
Longtime CEO John Holland became the company's chairman.[9]

In 2014, the company closed its Jamestown (Kentucky) plant, which had once
been the second manufacturing plant in the state, and laid off all 600
employees.[10] The company said it was moving the plant's operations to
[Honduras](/wiki/Honduras "Honduras") to reduce production costs.[11]
